shire, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1357–":"omkring 1357–Afdød","1357–Female":"1357–Afdød","1354–1390":"1354–1390","1360–1428":"1360–1428","1377–1430":"1377–1430","1383–Female":"1383–Afdød","–Male":"Afdød","–Female":"Afdød","1330–Male":"1330–Afdød","1330":"1330","abt 1383":"omkring 1383","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1390":"1390","1357":"1357","1455":"1455","1377":"1377","1354":"1354","1430":"1430","about 1357":"omkring 1357","about 1377":"omkring 1377","1428":"1428","Walworth, Durham, England":"Walworth, Durham, England","England":"England","South Kelsey, Lincolnshire, England":"South Kelsey, Lincolnshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1357–":"circa 1357–Overleden","1357–Female":"1357–Overleden","1354–1390":"1354–1390","1360–1428":"1360–1428","1377–1430":"1377–1430","1383–Female":"1383–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1330–Male":"1330–Overleden","1330":"1330","abt 1383":"circa 1383","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1390":"1390","1357":"1357","1455":"1455","1377":"1377","1354":"1354","1430":"1430","about 1357":"circa 1357","about 1377":"circa 1377","1428":"1428","Walworth, Durham, England":"Walworth, Durham, England","England":"England","South Kelsey, Lincolnshire, England":"South Kelsey, Lincolnshire, England"},"en":{"about 1357–":"about 1357–Deceased","1357–Female":"1357–Deceased","1354–1390":"1354–1390","1360–1428":"1360–1428","1377–1430":"1377–1430","1383–Female":"1383–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1330–Male":"1330–Deceased","1330":"1330","abt 1383":"about 1383","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1390":"1390","1357":"1357","1455":"1455","1377":"1377","1354":"1354","1430":"1430","about 1357":"about 1357","about 1377":"about 1377","1428":"1428","Walworth, Durham, England":"Walworth, Durham, England","England":"England","South Kelsey, Lincolnshire, England":"South Kelsey, Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gascoigne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern): habitational name from Anglo-Norman French <i>Gascon</i>, Middle English <i>Gascoun</i>, <i>Gascon</i> ‘Gascon, native of Gascony’ or the adjective <i>Gascuinz</i> ‘of Gascony’. The name of the region derives from that of the Basques, who are found close by and formerly extended into this region as well; they are first named in Roman sources as <i>Vascōnes</i>, but the original meaning of the name derived from a root <i>eusk-</i> in the non-Indo-European language that they still speak today, is completely obscure. By the Middle Ages the Basques had been displaced from most of Gascony by speakers of Gascon (a dialect of Occitan, related to French), who were proverbial for their boastfulness. In the 11th century Gascony united with Aquitaine and was thus held by England between 1154 and 1453."],"variants":[{"name":"Gaskin","meanings":["English: variant of   Gascoigne  ."]},{"name":"Gascon","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Jaime, Mario, Miguel, Rafael, Ruben, Amado, Ana, Ana Maria, Angel, Caridad.  French Andre, Chantal, Jean-Guy, Jean-Philippe, Monique, Serge, Simonne.","French; Spanish (<b>Gascón</b>): habitational name for someone from the province of Gascony, Old French <i>Gascogne</i> (see   Gascoigne  ). This surname is also found in Britain."]},{"name":"Gascoyne","meanings":["English (northern): variant of   Gascoigne  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret ","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":25,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705197,"age":98,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret  Gascoigne was born about 1357, in England as the daughter of Sir William Gascoigne. She had at least 3 sons and 3 daughters with Sir Robert Hansard II."},"et":{"about 1357–":"umbes 1357–Surnud","1357–Fe